#MEM id=systematic-debugging source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Technical/dev/skills/superpowers/systematic-debugging/condition-based-waiting.md savings=-3%
M|Over|tx|Flaky tests often guess at timing w/ arbitrary delays. This creates race conditions where tests pass on fast machines but fail under load or in CI.
M|Over|**Co|** Wait for the actual condition you care abt, not a guess abt how long it takes.
M|When|tx|```dot
M|When|tx|digraph when_to_use {
M|When|tx|"tst uses setTimeout/sleep?" [shape=diamond];
M|When|tx|"Testing timing behavior?" [shape=diamond];
M|When|tx|"Document WHY timeout needed" [shape=box];
M|When|tx|"Use condition-based waiting" [shape=box];
M|When|tx|"tst uses setTimeout/sleep?" -> "Testing timing behavior?" [label="yes"];
M|When|tx|"Testing timing behavior?" -> "Document WHY timeout needed" [label="yes"];
M|When|tx|"Testing timing behavior?" -> "Use condition-based waiting" [label="no"];
M|When|tx|}
M|When|tx|```
M|When|**Us|**
M|When|it|Tests have arbitrary delays (`setTimeout`, `sleep`, `time.sleep()`)
M|When|it|Tests are flaky (pass sometimes, fail under load)
M|When|it|Tests timeout when run in parallel
M|When|it|Waiting for async operations to complete
M|When|**Do|**
M|When|it|Testing actual timing behavior (debounce, throttle intervals)
M|When|it|Always document WHY if using arbitrary timeout
M|Core|tx|```ts
M|Core|// ❌|Guessing at timing
M|Core|tx|await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 50));
M|Core|tx|const result = getResult();
M|Core|tx|expect(result).toBeDefined();
M|Core|// ✅|Waiting for condition
M|Core|tx|await waitFor(() => getResult() !== undefined);
M|Core|tx|const result = getResult();
M|Core|tx|expect(result).toBeDefined();
M|Core|tx|```
M|Quic|tx|\| Scenario \| Pattern \|
M|Quic|tx|\|----------\|---------\|
M|Quic|tx|\| Wait for event \| `waitFor(() => events.find(e => e.tp === 'DONE'))` \|
M|Quic|tx|\| Wait for state \| `waitFor(() => machine.state === 'ready')` \|
M|Quic|tx|\| Wait for count \| `waitFor(() => items.length >= 5)` \|
M|Quic|tx|\| Wait for file \| `waitFor(() => fs.existsSync(path))` \|
M|Quic|tx|\| Complex condition \| `waitFor(() => obj.ready && obj.value > 10)` \|
M|Impl|Gene|
M|Impl|tx|```ts
M|Impl|tx|async fn waitFor<T>(
M|Impl|cond|() => T \| undefined \| null \| false,
M|Impl|desc|string,
M|Impl|tx|timeoutMs = 5000
M|Impl|)|Promise<T> {
M|Impl|tx|const startTime = Date.now();
M|Impl|tx|while (true) {
M|Impl|tx|const result = condition();
M|Impl|tx|if (result) return result;
M|Impl|tx|if (Date.now() - startTime > timeoutMs) {
M|Impl|tx|throw new er(`Timeout waiting for ${description} after ${timeoutMs}ms`);
M|Impl|tx|}
M|Impl|tx|await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 10)); // Poll every 10ms
M|Impl|tx|}
M|Impl|tx|}
M|Impl|tx|```
M|Impl|tx|See `condition-based-waiting-example.ts` in this directory for complete implementation w/ domain-specific helpers (`waitForEvent`, `waitForEventCount`, `waitForEventMatch`) from actual debugging sn.
M|Comm|**❌ |** `setTimeout(check, 1)` - wastes CPU
M|Comm|fix|** Poll every 10ms
M|Comm|**❌ |** Loop forever if condition never met
M|Comm|fix|** Always include timeout w/ clear er
M|Comm|**❌ |** Cache state before loop
M|Comm|fix|** Call getter inside loop for fresh data
M|When|tx|```ts
M|When|tx|// Tool ticks every 100ms - need 2 ticks to verify partial output
M|When|awai|wait for condition
M|When|awai|wait for timed behavior
M|When|tx|// 200ms = 2 ticks at 100ms intervals - documented and justified
M|When|tx|```
M|When|**Re|**
M|When|tx|1. First wait for triggering condition
M|When|tx|2. Based on known timing (not guessing)
M|When|tx|3. Comment explaining WHY
M|Real|From|
M|Real|it|Fixed 15 flaky tests across 3 files
M|Real|- Pa|60% → 100%
M|Real|- Ex|40% faster
M|Real|it|No more race conditions